  "response": "Getting into grad school with two C's depends on several factors:\n\n1. Overall GPA\n- If your overall GPA is still competitive (usually 3.0 or higher)\n- Your cumulative GPA matters more than individual grades\n\n2. School and Program\n- Some programs are more competitive than others\n- Highly selective schools have stricter requirements\n- Less competitive programs might be more flexible\n\n3. Other Application Strengths\n- Strong GRE/standardized test scores\n- Relevant work experience\n- Research experience\n- Strong recommendation letters\n- Compelling personal statement\n\n4. Grade Context\n- In what classes did you get C's?\n- Were they in major-related courses or general requirements?\n- Upward grade trend can help\n\n5. Potential Strategies\n- Explain circumstances behind lower grades\n- Take additional coursework to demonstrate academic ability\n- Consider post-baccalaureate programs\n- Apply to less competitive programs initially\n\nRecommendation:\n- Consult specific program admission requirements\n- Speak with admissions counselors\n- Consider strengths in other areas of application\n\nEach grad school and program evaluates applications holistically, so two C's don't automatically disqualify you.",
